The '''North Dakota Sports Hall of Fame''' is a hall of fame in the US state of [[North Dakota]] honoring individuals for athletic achievements. According to the Hall, its purpose is "to honor and recognize those individuals who have played a major role in the growth and development of sports in the state of North Dakota, and to further promote sports and sportsmanship to the public of North Dakota by so honoring those who have made outstanding contributions in sports."<ref>{{cite web|title=Sports Hall Of Fame|url=http://www.jamestownnd.org/departments/civic-center/sports-hall-of-fame|website=jamestownnd.org|publisher=City of Jamestown|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref> The Hall is located in the [[Jamestown Civic Center]] in [[Jamestown, North Dakota]].<ref name=Pool>{{cite news|last1=Pool|first1=Colton|title=Former Dickinson State football coach Biesiot elected to North Dakota Sports Hall of Fame|url=http://www.thedickinsonpress.com/sports/blue-hawks/3925208-former-dickinson-state-football-coach-biesiot-elected-north-dakota-sports|accessdate=May 4, 2017|work=The Dickinson Press|date=January 15, 2016}}</ref>
Inducted in 2016 were American football coach [[Hank Biesiot]]; ice hockey players and twin sisters [[Monique Lamoureux|Monique]] and [[Jocelyne Lamoureux]]; and former Major League Baseball player [[Travis Hafner]].<ref name=Pool/>
