{{COI|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox product | title = Skunklock | image = | image size = 250 | alt = A Skunklock locked to a bicycle. | image caption = Skunklock locked to a bicycle. | type = [[bicycle lock]] | inventor = [[Daniel Idzkowski]] and Yves Perrenoud<ref>{{cite news | last = Takahashi| first =Dean| title =SkunkLock fights back against bike thieves with pepper spray| work = [[VentureBeat]]| date =October 20, 2016| url = https://venturebeat.com/2016/10/20/skunklock-fights-back-against-bike-thieves-with-pepper-spray/ | accessdate = November 18, 2016 }}</ref> | launch year = 2017 | company = Skunklock | available = June 2017 {{small|(announced)}}<ref name=indiegogo>{{cite web |url= https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/skunklock-the-only-bike-lock-that-fights-back-bicycle#/ |title= Skunklock: The Bike Lock That Fights Back | website =[[indiegogo]] | access-date = November 18, 2016 |quote= "We hope to be able to ship to our earliest backers as early as April 2017, but because the compliance process cannot be easily predicted, we are guaranteeing June 2017 in time for summer."}}</ref> | current supplier = | last production = | models = | url = http://skunklock.com/ | notes = }}
The '''Skunklock''' is a brand of [[bicycle lock]] for securing a bicycle to a pole or other fixture, similar to a standard [[Bicycle lock#U-locks and D-locks|U-lock]]. Its cylindrical body contains a noxious chemical inside that is released if the body is cut. The chemical compound is meant as a deterrent to someone attempting to cut the lock and steal the bicycle. The lock is being funded through crowdfunding, with an announced shipping date of June 2017.<ref name=indiegogo/>
== Design == The Skunklock is constructed of [[Carbon steel#Medium-carbon steel|medium-carbon steel]]<ref>{{cite news | last = Liberatore| first = Stacy| title =The bike lock that stinks: SkunkLock can spray thieves with noxious chemical that makes them vomit and ruins their clothes| work = [[Daily Mail]]| date =October 20, 2016| url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-3856664/The-bike-lock-stinks-SkunkLock-spray-thieves-noxious-chemical-makes-vomit-ruins-clothes.html | accessdate = November 18, 2016 }}</ref> like a typical U-Lock, but contains a pressurized gas that will spray out if the lock is cut.<ref>{{cite news | last= Pequenino| first =Karla| title =The bicycle lock that fights thieves -- by making them sick| work =[[CNN]]| date =October 22, 2016| url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/21/world/skunklock-the-lock-that-fights-back-trnd/| accessdate =November 18, 2016 }}</ref>
The makers of Skunklock compare the effects to those of [[pepper spray]], but note that the formula for the chemical inside is proprietary. They say it will temporarily disable a thief by inducing vomiting in 99 percent of people, while making it difficult to see and breathe.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yuhas|first1=Alan|title=Bike lock developed that makes thieves immediately vomit|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/oct/21/bike-lock-developed-that-makes-thieves-immediately-vomit|accessdate=26 November 2016|work=The Guardian|date=20 October 2016}}</ref> The chemicals used are [[Food Chemicals Codex|food-grade]] and non-toxic, sharing chemical similarities to [[Surströmming|Swedish fermented herring]].<ref> {{cite news | last =Graff| first =Amy| title = SF company created a bike lock that makes thieves vomit| work =[[San Francisco Chronicle|SF Gate]]| date =October 21, 2016| url =http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/SkunkLock-bike-lock-emit-odor-vomit-thieves-10030466.php | accessdate =November 18, 2016 }}</ref>
Skunklock is being financed through a [[crowdfunding]] campaign on [[Indiegogo]], which launched in October 2016 with a goal of $20,000 in pre-orders. The makers announced later that month that they had achieved their funding goal.<ref>{{cite press release | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title =SkunkLock Successfully Funds World's First Deterrent Bike Lock| url =https://www.dropbox.com/sh/0dbjawb45w484qb/AAD-30b1AeR42soAdMKtwKDga/SkunkLock%20Funding%20Press%20Release.pdf?dl=0 | format = PDF | location = [[San Francisco]] | publisher =Skunklock | date =October 22, 2016| page =1| access-date = November 18, 2016 }}</ref>
